Why would plastic surgery be so wrong? I was complexed about a slightly abnormal part of my body since I was born (Most people never even noticed) but it was driving my so crazy and sad....in my early 20's I finally decided to go see a plastic surgeon. It only cost me 800$ and I have felt so much better about myself ever since. Why would I have paid for hours of therapy (which I also did, but for unrelated reasons....although hating your own body until you're in your 20s isn't great for self esteem.) Okay, maybe (probably) this person had plastic surgery too and it wasn't to "make her more normal", but so what? If that's how she wants to look, why shouldn't she be allowed to do so? You assume she necessarily did it because she wants to go to Hollywood and make millions.....so what? Even if that was true? What is so wrong with that? Not something I could be physically attracted to. But, it is fascinating to look at. In as much, as any really well done cosplay, with a lot of skill, attention to detail, and effort into it can be. As for what I think of surgical alterations to look like this. I believe the best and highest value of plastic surgery is reconstructive. Where-in someone needs it to cosmetically repair the results of injuries. Even so, Plenty of people have gotten procedures like gender re-assignment surgery. And, I think that feeling "right" in ones own body is a fair extension of surgery's use. I wouldn't be up in an outrage over some one who felt they had to become opposite the gender they were born to getting surgery to takes steps towards that. So, it would feel wrong to be upset about this.  All that said...While I feel tolerance, attempt at understanding, and eventually mainstream acceptance of what have long been considered alternate lifestyles, is a good thing. I still have a concern. That being plastic surgery as a drug. I wonder if people can get addicted to this. And, if sometimes it is can be considered unhealthy. Moreover, I wonder about societies responsibility to such individuals if it is really a thing. And, if this is an instance of needing to be your brothers keeper. or leaving well enough alone as long as it doesn't harm you personally.

I didn't notice the comma at first and I thought I saw a logic flaw. "Objectively, morally wrong," is logically correct because it lists "objectively," and "morally," as separate adjectives modifying "wrong."  "Objectively morally wrong," is logically incorrect because it shows "objectively," modifying "morally," instead of "wrong." This doesn't work because morals vary and cannot be objective.Â   I know this is nerdy and irrelevant but I hope someone learned something today from my blunder.

I am an anime fan...that looks creepy.Â  However, as he said, it's a free world.Â  I am disappointed in the attitude that she's doing this just to get famous though.Â  Some people engage in extreme body restructuring because that's what they want to look like for it's own end.Â  It's entirely possible that the fame is a simple byproduct.  In any case, no, most anime fans I know would not simply assume that they can pay a girl for companionship just because she goes to lengths to look like an anime character.Â  Most of the gamer, sci-fi and anime fans I know either have stable family lives or no interest in relationships at current.  Some of your attitudes betray a basic lack of understanding of what anime is.Â  Especially that there is more than one "anime" look.  The look she seems to be going for is the shoujo look, where the huge eyes are characteristic.Â  Shoujo being anime which is targeted at girls age 8 to 18.Â  So the comment about six year old Japanese boys is erroneous.Â  That tall, slender alien big-eyed look is one popular with girls 8 to 18 or women 18 to 40.Â   Shoujo generally revolves around romance, character development and magic (especially of the sparkly variety).Â   Some other anime/manga demographic targets:  Kodomo - children up to about age 8, very silly stuff like our own little kids cartoons  Shounen - young boys age 8 - 18, typically this focuses around fighting, friendship and superheroes of one stripe or another.Â  These are most similar to our adventure cartoons like Superman, X-Men, Johnny Quest and the like.  Seinen - younger men, ages 18-40.Â  This tends to delve into more philosophical content that younger audiences will either not understand or find boring.Â  They tend to be cynical, focus on intellectual pursuits, heavy into philosophical points.  Josei - younger women, ages 18-40.Â  This tends to focus on responsibility, the struggle between independence and dependence.Â  The question of love vs companionship or love vs romance.Â  Family is heavily important.  Silver and Golden - older audiences, these rarely are made into anime since older audiences buy less of the connected merchandise and even more rarely make it to the US...there's very little market for them here.Â   Educational manga - manga for teaching history, science, math, and so on abound.Â  Again, these aren't as often animated and left as manga comics.  Hobby manga - manga focused on techniques, new developments and interests regarding hobbies like golf, model building, baseball and so on.Â  Like the educational manga less in the way of story and more in the way of a cartoon magazine.Â  Also rarely animated.  The pornographic stuff isn't something I know too much about.Â  Americans will call it "hentai" which confuses Japanese because that word simply means "strange" or "weird".Â Â  Japanese seem to use the letter "H" (pronounced "ecchi") or the term "Ero" based on the English "erotic" to describe porn anime.Â  Oddly, Americans only use "ecchi" to describe the later soft-core stuff that is limited to frequent partial nudity and heavy sexual innuendo but rarely ever has actual sex acts.  I prefer to watch seinen stuff, though some of the more mature shounen is great and I've found more than a few shoujo and josei I like.Â  My appreciation of action, exciting and deep storylines, character development and romance means I often enjoy anime that appeals to multiple demographics.  The demographics that most match the cartoons we have here in the states are Shounen and Kodomo.

After further consideration, I'd like to correct myself. As outlandish as this may initially sound, it's most likely that your style is based on a fear of death. Bear with me.. Instinctively, humans are social beings, being that we desire the approval of others. This desire is an evolutionary hangover dating back to a time when being accepted into a group lead to a more successful chance to survive. Your choice in style is a reflection of that and how you feel the best way to achieve that is.

I understand all that. But you're not looking deep enough into the question of why it actually pleases you. It all comes down to a subconsciously underlying factor of what actually motivates us. Humans are on this planet to survive and procreate. The complicated emotions we feel and the actions we take either derive from our basic primal feelings towards the opposite sex.. (or sometimes same sex) or our fear of death. Although you may not be aware of it, your wardrobe is based on one those two.

Most often style is a combination of what the individual likes and what is well-known. Now, sometimes sexual attraction is a part of it, but not always, as this man is insinuating. If she likes anime and admires the look, chances are she's going to take what she likes and apply it to her own body and style for self-gratification; the same way I love the "flower child" look and apply it to my wardrobe.
